				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/25/business/smallbusiness/25paulstanding/25paulstanding-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/25/business/smallbusiness/25paulstanding/25paulstanding-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/25/business/smallbusiness/25paulstanding/25paulstanding-blog480.jpg" id="100000002962715" width="480" height="264" alt="Paul Downs: &quot;I hate doing employee reviews. I hate hearing that my workers wish that they had a better job when Iâm doing the best I can just to keep the doors open.&quot;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="264"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Paul Downs: "I hate doing employee reviews. I hate hearing that my workers wish that they had a better job when Iâm doing the best I can just to keep the doors open."</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Laura Pedrick for The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//boss.blogs.nytimes.com/category/staying-alive/">Staying Alive</a></h6><p class="summary">The struggles of a business trying to survive.</p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âGet the right people on the bus,â the business pundits like to say.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">This can be a messy process, at least in my experience. Over a series of posts this week, Iâd like to tell the story of how my desire to do a fair evaluation of my workers ended with a greatly disturbing result.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Take a trip with me back to a Thursday in February 2013. I am sitting with my department heads in our weekly Operations Committee meeting, which is devoted to identifying and solving problems on our shop floor. In the previous weekâs meeting, I had presented an analysis of our incoming orders for the previous 12 months, comparing the rate at which we were selling orders to the rate at which the shop was completing and shipping them. The sales team was outpacing the production team by more than 20 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I considered this very good news. At last, we had all the work we could handle. Unfortunately, a lot of new contracts are no guarantee of financial success. Profits are determined by comparing the value of what we ship in a given period with what we spend. And by that measure, things did not look so rosy. Spending was running neck and neck with production. Unless we could get the shop to operate more efficiently, we would not be able to take advantage of our newfound sales success. <span id="more-86091"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the beginning of this meeting, I was anticipating a discussion of technical issues. After the Operations Committee was established in November 2012, we had focused on small problems of limited scope, like specific fixes to machines or tweaks to the ways we built parts of our tables. The approach had led to some successes but had not increased efficiency enough to keep pace with incoming orders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I start each of these meetings with a question for the group: Are there any issues you want to talk about today? On this particular Thursday, my shop foreman, Kyle, raised his hand. âYou probably donât want to hear this,â he said, âbut there are some very unhappy people on the shop floor. I know that the sales guys are doing great and you are good with that, but some of the guys think that things arenât so great out there.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kyle was right â I did not want to hear this. I was thinking that we were finally doing really well, and we had an opportunity to do even better, if the shop floor could just get its act together. âUmmm, Iâm not sure what there is to be unhappy about,â I said. âBut if you think thereâs a problem, thereâs a problem. What do you want me to do about it?â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Kyle was ready with an answer: âWe need to have reviews.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Expletive deleted. I hate doing reviews. I hate coming up with the questions. I hate asking the questions. I hate hearing that my workers wish that they had a better job when Iâm doing the best I can just to keep the doors open. I hate the pressure to give everyone more money. And I hate the enormous amount of time involved. I had done them each year between 2006 and the crash in 2008 and then left off for a couple of years while I struggled to keep the business alive.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I did them again in 2010, but that time I didnât give anyone questions to answer. I told everyone that the reviews would not be about money, that I just wanted to sit with each of them individually and make sure they knew what I thought they should be doing. At the time, I was still handling all of the selling, and I was struggling to find the time and energy to be an effective leader. I simply could not make the review process any better than a one-way communication from boss to worker.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the time, there were only nine people on staff, and I think everyone was still too cowed by the weak economy to complain, for fear of being shown the door. Nobody protested. They listened carefully during their sessions, and the company did operate reasonably well during the next two years. But I donât think it was a positive experience for them, and I didnât feel all that great about it myself. Still, after it was over, I was able to say that I had reviewed everyone, and I hoped that I wouldnât have to do it again for a good long time.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">By the winter of 2013 I was in a different situation. Not only had the company emerged from the recession, we had almost doubled in size, to 17 workers. I had learned a lot since 2010 â much coming courtesy of helpful comments from my readers â and I had replaced myself as head salesman. I had a lot more time to devote to tasks that would make the company better. I had also decided that I would do much more to develop my people, so that I could push more of the responsibilities of running the company on to them. But before Kyle spoke up, a lot of my plans had been just talk. I had taken few steps to communicate the new vision. My Monday morning pep talks, apparently, werenât doing the job, and the Operations Committee meetings on Thursdays were too narrowly focused. As soon as Kyle finished talking, I realized he was right and that I needed to do a better job.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAll right,&#8221; I said, &#8220;I have been avoiding reviews, but itâs as good a time as any. I want to take some time to figure out a good way to do them. I have a <a href="//www.vistage.com/">Vistage</a> meeting next Tuesday. Iâll ask the group what they do for reviews, and then Iâll report back next week with what I find out. Weâll all look at this together and come up with a format that we all agree on. Then we can do the reviews in March.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Tuesday</strong>: <a href="boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/06/24/how-we-settled-on-a-format-for-employee-reviews/">How we picked a format for employee reviews</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Paul Downs founded <a href="//custom-conference-tables.com/">Paul Downs Cabinetmakers</a> in 1986. It is based outside Philadelphia.</em></p>
